data.name: label1.Text
data.value:
Maze Solver is an application written solely by Nikolas Andreou (Delirium) for the challenge given by e-Travel for the AFDEmp 1st Coding Bootcamp of Athens. The purpose of the application is to solve a maze loaded from a pre-formatted text file and provide the exit route to the end-user, both in text (in the form of coordinates) and visually. No third-party library has been used to achieve the end goal. The algorithm used to determine the exit path is a modified version of the Breadth-First Search (BFS) algorithm.
The goal has been achieved by huge brainstorming and a lot of help from every programmer's best friend, Google!

data.name: label2.Text
data.value: In order to solve a pre-defined maze (which must be contained in a text file), the user must first load it by clicking the "Load maze from file button". The string containing the maze will be verified for legitimacy and if it's valid, it will be loaded in the visual representation picture box on the form. Walls are marked with a different color form walkable tiles, same as the entrance and exit blocks (also known as nodes). When the "Solve maze" button is clicked, the solution path will be drawn in the visual representation and the solution logs field will be populated with the coordinates of the nodes that have been walked to find the exit.

data.name: label3.Text
data.value: In the manual edit mode and as long as no maze has been loaded from a file (in this case, click the "Clear maze" button to reset the visual representation), you can create your own maze by clicking on the blocks to create walls. When walls are created and you wish to solve the maze, exit manual edit mode and click on a block to mark it as the entrance. Then drag your mouse to your desired exit block, to form the visual path of the solution.

data.name: label5.Text
data.value: The maze blueprint file structure should be a text file containing the rows and columns o the maze defined by arithmetic values. Each column of each row must be separated from the previous one with a comma (,) and each row should be separated from the previous one with a new line. Walkable tiles are marked with 0, entrance tile is marked with 1, exit tile is marked with 2 and walls are marked with 3. An example maze blueprint is on the right. Right click to save it.
